asking how such institutions can be reformed. Writing with coauthors ranging from a prominent cardiologist to long-term inmates, he explores alternative environments that can better humanize—even spiritualize—the way we treat one another, offering a very different vision of medical, criminal justice, and food systems. Ultimately Leder proposes not just new answers to important bioethical questions but new ways of questioning accepted concepts and practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFactory farms - Philosophy. 0aFactory farmsxPhilosophy. 0aHuman body (Philosophy) 0aHuman body (Philosophy). 0aImprisonmentxPhilosophy. 0aMedicinexPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  abioethics.  aillness.  aimprisonment.  amedicine.  aorgan transplants.  apain.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022639607140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226396248423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226396248/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles